{"title_page": "Oriri", "text_new": "{{Infobox book\n| name          = Oriri\n| title_orig    =\n| translator    =\n| image         =Oriri_book_cover,_Marie_Stopes.jpg\n| caption       =\n| author        = [[Marie C. Stopes]]\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  =\n| country       =\n| language      = English\n| subject       = \n| genre         =  \n| publisher     = Heinemann \n| pub_date      = September 1940\n| english_pub_date =\n| media_type    =\n| pages         = 30\n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   =\n}}\n\n'''''Oriri''''' (1940) is a long poem by the birth control pioneer [[Marie Stopes|Marie C. Stopes]], published by Heinemann as a short book. Its subject is love between a \"He\" and a \"She\", and it is written in semi-dramatic form, with other members of the cast including \"Spirits of Air\", \"Spirits of Earth\" and other \"Elementals\". Stopes writes in the \"Argument\" that prefaces the poem: \"Interwoven in the tale is a crystallisation of most of what matters fundamentally in the sciences of geology and physiology, in the art of love, and in religion.\" <ref>Marie C. Stopes, ''Oriri''</ref>\n\nThe poem brings together Stopes' scientific knowledge (she held a doctorate in [[paleobotany]]) with her theory of \"erogamic love\" (lifelong erotic pair-bonding), the latter of which was an important component of the theories that underlay her most influential and controversial publication, the [[sex manual]] ''[[Married Love]]'' (1918). In her biography of Stopes, Ruth Hall suggests that the poem was written when Stopes was in love with Keith Briant, a recent Oxford graduate who was considerably her junior <ref>Ruth Hall, ''Marie Stopes: A Biography'' (Andre Deutsch, 1977), p. 287</ref>(Stopes was just short of her sixtieth birthday when she wrote the poem).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n*\n*\n*\n*\n\n[[Category:1940 poems]]\n[[Category:1940 poetry books]]\n[[Category:Heinemann (publisher) books]]\n[[Category:Love poems]]\n[[Category:British poetry books]]\n[[Category:British poems]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book\n| name          = Oriri\n| title_orig    =\n| translator    =\n| image         =Oriri_book_cover,_Marie_Stopes.jpg\n| caption       =\n| author        = [[Marie C. Stopes]]\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  =\n| country       =\n| language      = English\n| subject       = \n| genre         =  \n| publisher     = Heinemann \n| pub_date      = September 1940\n| english_pub_date =\n| media_type    =\n| pages         = 30\n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   =\n}}\n\n'''''Oriri''''' (1940) is a long poem by the birth control pioneer [[Marie Stopes|Marie C. Stopes]], published by Heinemann as a short book. Its subject is love between a \"He\" and a \"She\", and it is written in semi-dramatic form, with other members of the cast including \"Spirits of Air\", \"Spirits of Earth\" and other \"Elementals\". Stopes writes in the \"Argument\" that prefaces the poem: \"Interwoven in the tale is a crystallisation of most of what matters fundamentally in the sciences of geology and physiology, in the art of love, and in religion.\" <ref>Marie C. Stopes, ''Oriri''</ref>\n\nThe poem brings together Stopes' scientific knowledge (she held a doctorate in [[paleobotany]]) with her theory of \"erogamic love\" (lifelong erotic pair-bonding), the latter of which was an important component of the theories that underlay her most influential and controversial publication, the [[sex manual]] ''[[Married Love]]'' (1918). In her biography of Stopes, Ruth Hall suggests that the poem was written when Stopes was in love with Keith Briant, a recent Oxford graduate who was considerably her junior <ref>Ruth Hall, ''Marie Stopes: A Biography'' (Andre Deutsch, 1977), p. 287</ref>(Stopes was just short of her sixtieth birthday when she wrote the poem).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n*\n*\n*\n*\n\n[[Category:1940 poems]]\n[[Category:1940 books]]\n[[Category:Heinemann (publisher) books]]\n[[Category:Love poems]]\n[[Category:British poetry books]]\n[[Category:British poems]]\n", "name_user": "I grieve in stereo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:1940 bookstoCategory:1940 poetry booksusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oriri"}
